MissionCommands.Message: Good morning {{profileName}}, today we will learn how to use the SPS engine located on the Service Module to modify our current orbit.
In the previous lessons we learned how to use the Command Module Computer (Apollo Guidance Computer), how to operate the SPS engine, as well as a brief introduction to the auto-maneuvering features.
In this lesson we will use all of these technologies to make controlled changes to our orbit, using the SPS burn planning tool.
We will learn the ideal way of performing burns using the Command Module Computer programs P30 (setup), P52 (alignment) and P40 (execute the burn).
Let us enable the A/C ROLL jets as they will be needed during this lesson.

Then set the CMC MODE to FREE to prevent using fuel during our burn preparations. This is basically the manual control mode of the Apollo primary guidance, navigation, and control system (PGNCS, pronounced pings).
We are currently in orbit around Earth, in a CSM-only configuration. Please check the BRIEFING page on your MISSION PAD before moving on.
Go to the ORBITAL VIEW using the View Selector, and select the EARTH view mode. Orient the view so you can see your orbital trajectory.
Open the Communication/Tools menu (by default assigned to keyboard [C]), and click on the BURN PLANNER. You can toggle of the Communication/Tools/View Selectors to declutter the screen.
This opens the MANEUVER PLANNER for the CSM. This tool is used to plan orbital changes using the SPS engine.
It has three parameters you can use to plan your burn. The first is the phase of where in the orbit the burn should take place, then it's the delta V, and finally the burn direction.
Let's start with the phase. Set the phase value to 40 by clicking on the input box and pressing 40.
The phase is one of the orbital parameters used to indicate your position in space. Given an orbit, the phase tells you where in the orbit you are using an angle.
The phase angle starts from zero at Perigee (Pe) in your current orbit.
The phase angle can be any value between 0 and 360 degrees. A Phase of 180 degrees marks your Apogee (Ap).
Next is the amount of velocity change we want the burn to make. Set this value to 100. This means we wish to plan a burn with a dV of 100 feet/second.
The last parameter is the direction of the burn. Set this to PROGRADE.
A phase of 40 will set the ignition time just above the Gulf of Mexico. With all the parameters set, you can see the estimated trajectory (orange line) and burn data in the tool.

When you request a burn, Mission Control will communicate the parameters to you and uplink the data to the CMC. Requesting a burn will start this process, and you will receive two messages containing burn information and parameters. Press REQUEST now and then ROGER on the two burn data messages.
The burn parameter messages contains the P30 MANEUVER PAD. PAD stands for Pre-Advisory Data.

A PAD is made up of multiple data fields that brief the crew on the key parameters of a planned maneuver. These fields usually cover event timings such as ignition, required spacecraft attitude, target delta-V, the predicted post-maneuver orbit, and other details.

A PAD is verbally transmitted to the crew by the CAPCOM and plotted into a specific form by the crew. The P30 MANUEVER PAD is also accompanied by a data uplink that loads the maneuver information directly into the Command Module Computer (CMC) memory.
Let us take a look at a P30 PAD. Press [C] to toggle the COMMs menu, and press CREW MEMBERS -> REQUEST PADS & CHARTS -> COMMAND MODULE: OPEN P30 MANEUVER PAD FORM.

As you can see, this PAD contains many data fields related to a burn. On the menu bar of the PAD window you will see an Autoplot button. Press this to fill out the PAD or use the tools to manually fill it out. Press ROGER when done.

The next step will be to set up the burn in the CMC. Enter the cockpit again and get a good view of the CMC. Mission Control has already set the values into the memory of the CMC, so our job will be to verify and make changes if needed.
Key V37E 30E to start program 30, the external delta V program. This program is used to set up a burn using the SPS, with data from outside of the CMC, such as from the tool we just used.
As P30 loads, Noun 33 will show the Ground Elapsed Time of Ignition (GETI), where register 1 contains the hours, register 2 contains the minutes, and register 3 contains seconds and milliseconds.

It has the following format: R1: 00XXX hours, R2: 000XX minutes, and R3: 0XX.XX seconds. The decimal in the R3 format is imaginary as the DSKY is not capable of drawing decimals. You can use the tables in the Flight Manual to look up the formats of each digit.
As an example, let us say the ignition time is set to GET 001:31:11, so 1 hour, 31 minutes and 11.00 seconds. Register 1 would be +00001, register 2 would be +00031, and register 3 would be +01100.
Verify that the three registers matches the PAD. To accept the data, press PRO to proceed.

Noun 81 shows the planned delta velocity (dV) where each field has the format of XXXX.X ft/s. It should be set to about 100.0 fps from the uplink (you can ignore the fractional differences). This data is the magnitude and direction of the burn from the local vertical frame on ignition [Delta V X,Y,Z (LV)]. Press PRO to proceed.

The CMC will spend some time calculating the results of the burn, and present the results for you. R1 and R2 shows your Ap and Pe after the burn (format: XXXX.X nmi), and R3 shows the velocity in fps (format: XXXX.X ft/s). Press PRO to proceed.

Noun 45 will then count down towards the burn. This value can maximum be 59 minutes and 59 seconds. The Digital Event Timer is frequently used during various maneuvers like for example a burn, and is an important tool to learn.
The Digital Event Timer (DET) is operated on panel 1. Let us first stop it, so flip the EVENT TIMER mode to STOP.
Look up between the LV ENGINE lights and the ABORT light so see 4 digits. The first two represents minutes, and the latter two seconds, and is read as 00:00. Verify that this is stopped.
RESET the Digital Event Timer (DET) back to 00:00 by flipping the direction switch to RESET/UP.
Verify that the Digital Event Timer (DET) display reads 00:00.
This switch will modify the minutes of the Digital Event Timer (DET). Flipping it UP will increas the minutes by 10. Flipping it down will increase the minutes by 1.
This switch will modify the seconds of the Digital Event Timer (DET). Flipping it UP will increas the seconds by 10. Flipping it down will increase the seconds by 1.

Use these controls to set the Digital Event Timer (DET) to 20:00 (20 minutes, 00 seconds). Press ROGER when the timer reads 20:00. If you make mistakes you can flip the direction switch to RESET again.
The counting direction switch has three positions, RESET (up), UP (middle), and DOWN (down). Set it to DOWN as we want to count down from 20:00

Look at the DSKY where register 3 is counting down towards the burn (if it displays 59:59 it's still counting down but too large to display). Use Timescale until the countdown is at about 20 minutes and 30 seconds before the burn.
We are now 20 minutes away from the ignition time. Start the Digital Event Timer (DET).
Press PRO to end P30. The CMC will automatically return to P00.
Next we will need to align the reference platform stored in the Inerial Measurement Unit with the burn direction. To do this, will will use Program 52.

The Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) is responsible for maintaining the reference platform of the craft and is frequently changed based on what mission phase you are in. It is a fixed inertial platform (fixed relative to the stars). This platform is what the craft use to calculate its attitude (roll, pitch, yaw) from.
Key V37E 52E
Let P52 load, Verb 04 Noun 06 will show when P52 is ready.
Ok, P52 is ready. Key V22E 1E on the DSKY. This will change R2 to 00001. Verify this, and press PRO.
Verb 06 Noun 22 shows the torqing angles. Press PRO to accept and align the Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) with the "preferred" attitude, in this case, being the direction of the burn.
This means the reference platform is changed so that if the crew maintains the attitude 0,0,0, the craft will be perfectly pointed into the planned burn direction.
Let us start an automaneuver towards the 0,0,0 attitude. Key V49E V25E +0E +0E +0E to set Roll, Pitch, Yaw to 0,0,0. Verify the data.
Set the CMC MODE to AUTO.
Key PRO PRO to start the automaneuver. You will notice that V50 changes to V06 and that the rate indicators on FDAI 1 shows an angular rate. Press ROGER when this happens.
Auto-maneuver is a very slow process, with 0.2 degrees/second (depending on your DAP setup). The CSM is designed to maneuver slow to save fuel.

Note: If the two DIRECT switches are set to UP, you can help the manuver by the cost of additional fuel. If the RHC (Rotational Hand Controllers) are ON, and DIRECT is OFF, any stick deflection will cancel the manuever, revert it to Attitude Hold (if you want to manually complete the manuever), and V50 will show again. The automaneuver can then be restarted by pressing PRO again.
When the maneuver is complete, it will change back to V50. When this happens, press ROGER.
Press ENTR to end the automaneuvering routine. It is important to end all routines before running other programs on the computer.
Verify that the DSKY is blank and that Program 00 (P00) is running.
The next part is to start P40 - SPS Program. On the CMC, insert V37E 40E.
Ensure that the CSM is under CMC auto control.

The first thing you will see is a flashing V50N18. This is the CMC requesting to maneuver the CSM to the desired FDAI angles for auto-maneuver. This is similar to the V49 auto maneuver we just did. Press PRO to accept the maneuver.

Verb 06 has now replaced Verb 50, indicating that the auto maneuver is in progress. Note that Noun 18 is still visible, and all registers should be zero, as this is our target burn attitude, meaning we desire a prograde attitude.
Verify on the FDAI that the attitude is correct and matches the CMC, and verify that V50 N18 shows. Press PRO to proceed.
This will once again trim the maneuver. You will see V06 N18 show briefly before V50 is displayed, indicating that the trim is complete.

Once again, verify the attitude and that the CMC displays V50N18. Press ENTR to reject another automaneuver, terminating the automaneuvering routine (R60) and returning the P40 flow. You should see V50N25.
Next the CMC asks you to perform an optional checklist (204, SPS gimbal trim test). Press ENTR to skip this now.
Noun 40 is now counting down to the burn. Use time scale to -02:00 minutes before the burn.

Let's arm the SPS engine. On panel 1, set the dV THRUST A to ARM (up). These switches are protected by a cover that needs to be open for the entire burn. Closing the cover will also push the switch below it down, disarming the engine.
Verify that the attitude is prograde, and pay attention to the countdown. When it's 5 seconds left to the burn, V99 shows, asking for your permission to ignite. Press PRO to allow.

Ignition - V06 indicate burn in progress. Once it changes to V16, the burn is complete. R2 is counting up, showing the dV still required by the burn. When this is 0, the SPS engine will automatically shut down.
Cutoff! Notice that V16 should be visible indicating burn completion. Press PRO to proceed.
Noun 85 will now show the residuals (not yet implemented), skip this step and press PRO.
Return to P00.
You can now use V82E to see your current orbit.
You can also go to the ORBITAL VIEW to see your new orbit.
You now have a good overview of how to plan a burn, align the craft and its attitude with it, and execute a burn. Let us create another similar burn but this time, we will use the checklists.
Open the Burn Planner again.
Press RESET PLANNER to clean up after the previous burn. You should always do this before planning a new burn.
The goal of the next burn is to circulate the orbit. We can do this by creating a burn at Apogee. Apogee is always at phase 180, so set Phase to 180.
Set the dV to 100.
Ensure the direction is set to PROGRADE. The resulting burn should now show a ~circular orbit of about 160 nmi alt. Feel free to tweak it if you feel confident. Press REQUEST.
If you closed the P30 MANUVER PAD, re-open it by pressing CREW MEMBERS -> REQUEST PADS & FORMS -> COMMAND MODULE: P30 MANUEVER PAD FORM.
On its toolbar, press the pen-shaped button to enter EDIT PAD mode, then press "Clear" on the edit mode toolbar to remove the old PAD data.
Press the lock-shaped button to exit EDIT PAD mode, then press "Autoplot" to insert the new P30 MANEUVER PAD data into the form.

The burn has been uplinked to the computer along with the previous PAD parameters. Do not RUN the checklist but you can reference the P30 steps by opening the MISSION PAD -> CHECKLISTS -> (AoH) COMMAND MODULE -> PRETHRUSTING: (P30) EXTERNAL V.
Key V37E 30E to set up the burn.
Press PRO on Noun 33 to accept the Time of Ignition (TIG).
Noun 81 will show the dV. Verify the data and press PRO to accept.
Noun 42 shows the resulting orbit. Press PRO.
Noun 45 counts down for the burn. Let us reset and set the Digital Event Timer.
Then use the EVENT TIMER set switches to set it to 20:00 minutes.
Use time scale. When the DSKY indicates 20:00 minutes left to the burn, we will start the DET.
T -20:00, start the DET, then press PRO on the DSKY to end P30.
Ensure you have no running checklists (press CLEAR ALL if you do) and RUN the G&N ALIGNMENTS -> P52 AID: PREFERRED checklist. You can reference the P52 IMU Realign checklist if you wish.
Follow the checklist to complete the P52 Option 1 (Preferred) procedure.
Great! The IMU has been aligned with the new burn direction.
Next open (but do not RUN) the MISSION PAD -> CHECKLISTS -> (AoH) COMMAND MODULE -> THRUSTING: (P40) G&N SPS THRUSTING checklist and reference it. I will take you through all the steps.
With the burn planned, P30 all set up, and the IMU aligned with the preferred (burn direction) attitude using P52, we can use V49E to automaneuver to the burn attitude.
Key V49E and ensure all values are zero.
Then start the automaneuver.
V06 indicates that the maneuver is in progress. When it returns to V50, the maneuver is complete. When this happens, press ROGER.
Press ENTR to complete the automaneuvering routine and verify that you are in P00.
Let us set up the Entry Monitoring System. It can be used to monitor our dV maneuvers, as a backup to the computer. Set the EMS Function to V.

You can press the thumb rocker switch to increase the V/RANGE value. In this mode, this is V, not RANGE. The thumb rocker is divided into 4 sections: +10, +0.1, -0.1, -10. For example, pressing the upper part increases it by 10. Try this now.
Use the thumb rocker to set the EMS V to +100.0. Press ROGER when complete.
Set the EMS Function to V. This will allow it to start tracking our V changes when its mode is set to NORMAL (something that we will do later).
Then zero the optics (you will learn more about this in the optics lesson).
Key V37E 00E to ensure P00.
Key V37E 40E to start P40, the SPS thrusting program.
V50 N18 is flashing. This indicates another automaneuver designed to trim our previous manuever (V49E). Ensure the CMC mode is still AUTO, then press PRO to start the automaneuver.
V50 will change to V06 to indicate that the maneuver is in progress. It will change back to V50 when the maneuver is complete. When this happens, press ROGER.
Wait until it's 10:00 minutes until ignition.
We will now connect battery A and B to help offload the power load during the burn. Monitor battery bus A.
While monitoring the battery bus A voltage and amps, set the MAIN BUS TIE to BAT A/C (up). Notice an increase in amps and a decrease in volts.
Let us do the same for battery bus B.
While monitoring the battery bus B voltage and amps, set the MAIN BUS TIE to BAT B/C (up). Notice an increase in amps and a decrease in volts.
We will set the Thrust Vector Control (TVC) of the SPS engine to Rate Command in pitch and yaw.
Then we will set the Thrust Vector Control (TVC) SPS gimbal drive to AUTO to allow automatic control.
We will then power the Thrust Vector Control (TVC) servos.
We enable manual translation control to allow umbilical thrusting (not needed today), and tuning our orbit after the burn is complete.
We will then test the Manual Thrust Vector Control (MTVC) capabilities in case we need to manually take over (not going to happen today).
Turn on the TVC 1 gimbal motor for pitch.
Turn on the TVC 1 gimbal motor for yaw.
Let us monitor the gimbal trim on the Gimbal Position Indicator (GPI).
The gimbal data will then be visible on the GPI.
Reset the gimbal trim thumb wheels to zero.

Press [C] to toggle ON the Function Bubbles. On the Translation Hand Controller (THC) located on the left armrest of the left hand seat, you will see three function bubbles. One is CCW (counter clockwise), NEUT (neutral). and CW (clockwise). Press ROGER when you have found these.

Press to (CW) function bubble to rotate the Translation Hand Controller (THC) handle to the right (clockwise). This modes it into SCS mode, allowing Manual Thrust Vector Control (MTVC). Press ROGER when you have turned the handle CW.

However, TVC GIMBAL MOTORS 1 (pitch and yaw) does not contain Manual Thrust Vector Control (MTVC) capabilities. Test this by sending attitude commands using your attitude control keys ([W][S] for pitch, [A][D] for yaw). The gimbal needles on the GPI should not move when sending input commands. Press ROGER when done.
Turn on the TVC 2 gimbal motor for pitch.
Turn on the TVC 2 gimbal motor for yaw.
The TVC 2 gimbal motors provide MTVC. Try to send attitude input commands now and notice that the gimbals will move with the deflection ([W][S] for pitch, [A][D] for yaw). Press ROGER when verified.

Switch the THC back to Neutral by pressing the (NEUT) function bubble. This is very important. Verify that the THC handle is back to its normal center alignment again (neutral mode). Press ROGER when verified.
This completes the MTVC capabilities test.
We will now configure back to the normal attitude contol mode for a P40 burn.
V50 N18 should still be visible on the DSKY. Press PRO for a final trim of the attitude. Press ROGER when V50 changes to V06.
When V50 is once again displayed, press ENTR to stop the auto maneuvering routine and proceed with the P40 flow.
V50 N25 is now displaying checklist code 204, the gimbal trim test. This time we will complete this test. Monitor the GPI gauges again, then press PRO.
You will see that the gimbals are moving in a pattern where pitch up, pitch down, yaw left and yaw right commands are tested. They will each deflect +/-2 degrees.
The CMC automatically transitioned to V06 N40 when the gimbal check was complete. You will now see the countdown towards the burn. Wait until T -02:00 minutes until the burn.
At T-00:35 the DSKY clears the display for 5 seconds, then returns at T -00:30.
This allows the EMS to monitor our burn as configured earlier. When the DSKY shows V99, press PRO to accept the burn.
Ignition! This is a short burn and when complete, the engine should automatically cutoff. The dV should count down. If not, something went wrong and you should re-attempt the lesson.
Cutoff! Great job. The rest of the procedures is to reset all the systems back to normal.
Press PRO on the DSKY until P40 returns to P00.

There you go! Today you learned the basics of how to execute a burn, the main flow of how every burn should be executed (Plan, P30, P52 opt 1, V49E to 0,0,0 and P40), and all the procedures related to a P40 burn.
Good job, this completes the lesson.

Title: Lesson 8 - Planning SPS Burns
Description: The SPS burn planner tool is meant to help you maneuver in space. It is used to plan short burns to change your current orbit, de-orbiting burns as well as the Lunar Orbit Insertion burn and Trans-Earth Injection. All of these burns relies on the SPS, and the CMC.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

In this lesson we will take a look at the SPS burn tool and how to use it to maneuver in space.

To use the tool, you will need to first select where in your current orbit you wish that your burn will take place. To set the burn position, you will need to use the phase of your current orbit. The phase is an angle between 0 and 360 degrees, and represents your position in a given orbit. A phase angle of 0 degrees is the orbits Pe position, while a phase angle of 180 degrees is Ap. A phase between 0 and 180 is somewhere between Pe and Ap, on the way towards Ap, while a phase angle between 180 and 360 is somewhere between Ap and Pe, on the way to Pe from Ap.

The second input required by the tool is the amount of delta V the burn will have. This is the amount of velocity change given in ft/s.

The last input is the direction of the burn.

Based on these inputs, the tool will give you an estimate of your new orbit, when the engine needs to ignite. If you are satisfied, press REQUEST, and mission control will communicate the details with you, as well as uplinking the data into your CMC.

To prepare for the burn after using the tool, and pressing REQUEST, you need to first run P30 (External Delta V Program) on the CMC to set the burn, P52 to align the IMU, and then use P40 (SPS Program) to execute and monitor the burn itself.
